      "@type": "PriceSpecification",
      "price": "120.00",
      "priceCurrency": "USD",
      "description": "Commercial diagnostic fee, applied toward repair"
    }
  }
})} />

<script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does commercial dishwasher repair cost?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Our commercial diagnostic fee is $120, applied toward the repair once you approve the work. Most commercial dishwasher repairs run between $180 and $500. Wash pump motor, spray arm replacement, door latch, heating element, or chemical dispenser is toward the lower end. Control board replacement runs higher. We provide a full written estimate before any work begins."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Which areas of Southern California do you cover?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "All five SoCal counties: Los Angeles, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, and Riverside. We dispatch from 8 service territories so the technician on your commercial call is coming from the closest one. Same-day commercial priority dispatch across all 5 counties."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My commercial dishwasher is not reaching sanitizing temperature, is this a health code issue?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. County health authorities across SoCal (LA County DPH, OC Health Care Agency, Ventura County Environmental Health, San Bernardino DEHS, Riverside County DEH) all require commercial dishwashers to reach either 140°F for chemical sanitizing machines or 180°F final rinse for high-temperature machines per CalCode. A machine that's washing but not sanitizing is a health code violation, not just a performance issue. Inspectors check final rinse temperature during routine inspections. If your machine isn't reaching spec, stop relying on it for sanitizing and call us immediately."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My commercial dishwasher is not cleaning dishes properly, what causes that?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The most common cause across Southern California is clogged spray arms from mineral scale, SoCal's hard water (300–400 mg/L TDS; Inland Empire wells often higher) deposits calcium inside spray arm holes, reducing water distribution and pressure. Other causes: failed wash pump motor reducing water pressure, depleted detergent/chemical dispenser, or water temperature below spec. We descale spray arms and check all four factors before recommending part replacement."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why are my glasses coming out cloudy from the commercial dishwasher?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Cloudy glassware across SoCal is almost always mineral scale from regional hard water depositing on glass surfaces during drying. Two solutions: a properly functioning rinse aid dispenser (rinse aid prevents scale adhesion during the final rinse), and a water softener or treatment system on the incoming water line. If your rinse aid dispenser is not functioning correctly, scale will accumulate regardless of detergent quality. We check and service chemical dispensers on every commercial dishwasher call."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you repair Jackson commercial dishwashers?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Jackson is the most common commercial dishwasher brand across SoCal restaurants and food service operations. We carry parts for Jackson specifically, wash pump motors, spray arms, door latches, and heating elements. The Jackson WWS series and Conserver series are the models we service most frequently."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How often should a commercial dishwasher be serviced?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Every 6 months minimum. A service visit includes descaling spray arms and internal components, checking and calibrating wash and rinse temperatures against health code spec, inspecting the chemical dispenser and dosing, door gasket condition check, and pump motor assessment. In SoCal's hard water environment, descaling every 3–4 months is the practical standard for high-volume operations."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "When does it make sense to repair vs replace a commercial dishwasher?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Commercial dishwashers (Jackson, Hobart, Champion) are built for 12-15 year service lives with proper maintenance. Repair almost always makes sense unless the wash tank is corroded through (typically only on units 15+ years old that haven't been descaled regularly). Replacement runs $5,000–$25,000+ for a new unit plus installation, plumbing, and electrical, a major capital outlay. We give you an honest assessment during the diagnostic."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My commercial dishwasher is leaking, what should I do?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Turn off the machine and stop using it, water on a commercial kitchen floor is a slip hazard and a health inspection issue. Common causes: failed door gasket (water leaking from door edges), overfill from a faulty water inlet valve, or a damaged pump seal. We can typically diagnose and repair same-day. Document the leak location if you can, it helps us bring the right parts."
      }
    }
  ]
})} />

